This course focuses on developing students\' critical reading and writing skills in the areas of international relations and contemporary history. Students work on producing four finished pieces of analytical writing in two styles. These are complementary assignments that, combined, enhances understanding of the nature, purpose, and future of U.S. hegemony or global dominance. &#8232;&#8232;

Students thought this course was \"great,\" \"interesting,\" and \"fun.\" They especially applauded the productive structure and pace of the course, noting that the \"amount covered was impressive.\" Some students, though, felt that the lectures were sometimes too repetitive of the readings.

Students heaped praise upon Professor Horowitz, describing him as \"great,\" \"engaging,\" and \"extremely knowledgeable.\" He was noted for presenting ideas effectively and for his ability to \"stimulate students to study about American foreign policies.\" Students also thought that Professor Horowitz was \"fun\" and a \"dynamic speaker.\"&#8232;&#8232;

Students felt that there was \"too much reading\" in the course, although these readings were \"well tied into class.\" Students wished that the readings were \"more varied.\"

This course examines the politics of international economic relations. Whether we are considering trade or monetary issues among rich countries, or problems of debt and development for emerging economies, an understanding of how economic policies and outcomes are affected by politics is essential. Economic theories of trade and finance allow us to identify the potential gains from exchange between countries, but only by systematically analyzing domestic and international politics can we explain the actual patterns of exchange that we observe. The course will analyze the interplay between politics and economics in three broad areas: international trade, international finance, and economic development. In each section, we will first discuss economic theories that explain the causes and consequences of international commerce, capital flows, and economic growth. We will then explore how political interests, institutions, and ideas alter these predictions, examining both historical examples and current policy debates.

Students felt this was a wonderful course and a “great introduction into International Political Economy.” By covering up-to-date issues, the course gave students a framework to understand the actions of governments and other actors. Students felt that the professor did a great job of having the readings compliment the lectures. However, one student did feel that real life examples were needed to ground the theory readings. &#8232;&#8232;

Professor Schulz is described as a “well-organized” professor who taught the concepts very clearly. He was also praised for his willingness to hold discussion and questions in lecture and to review the readings. Yet students did find that the Professor could be a bit dry at times. One student said Professor Schulz was “a bit hard to understand which made it hard to gain full benefit of what he was saying.”&#8232;&#8232;

This is a political science elective course.

This is an undergraduate lecture course examining the role that international law and institutions play in international relations. The course begins by exploring broad theoretical questions—questions about why states create international law and international relations; how states design institutions; the impact that institutional design may have on the effectiveness of international relations; and the conditions under which states are likely to comply with the rules set out by international institutions and the dictates of international law. The remainder of the course is organized topically, looking at how international institutions and law function in various arenas of international affairs. Topics include collective security institutions such as the League of Nations, the United Nations, and NATO; human rights law; the laws of war; international intervention and peacekeeping; international justice and the International Criminal Court; environmental law; international trade law and the World Trade Organization; economic development and the World Bank; and international finance and the role of the International Monetary Fund.&#8232;

&#8232;Students felt the course was very organized and thorough. Some felt that it would have helped to spend less time on theory and more on real-world examples. One student thought it was too similar to PSCI 150 International Relations Theory and Practice. Another student complained that “expectations for the quality of work were a little high; it was not clear how to achieve an A, or how to improve grades after.” Most students also said that there was too much reading that was unnecessarily verbose and long. &#8232;&#8232;

Professor Stanton has been complimented as a great teacher. Students felt she was an “intelligent, great resource” who “explains the material really well.” Students said Professor Stanton came to class well prepared, was very accessible, and always willing to answer questions. Some suggested that Professor Stanton’s lectures could be a bit dry and would have preferred she conducted lecture in a less rigid and rehearsed manner.

This course is a Political Science elective course.

This course will provide an overview of major figures and themes of modern political thought. Instead of providing a comprehensive survey (a smattering of all possible figures) the course will instead provide a more detailed study of 7 or 8 major figures in the modern canon from the 17th to 19th centuries, reading significant selections from several of their most important works. In the process, we will explore more general themes and questions pertinent to political theory in the modern era, particularly focusing on the relationship of the individual to community, society, and state. Although the emergence of the individual as a central moral, political, and conceptual category arguably began in earlier eras, it is in the seventeenth century that it takes firm hold in defining the state, political institutions, moral thinking, and social relations. The centrality of “the individual” has created difficulties, even paradoxes, for community and social relations, and political theorists have struggled to reconcile those throughout the modern era. We will consider the political forms that emerged out of those struggles, as well as the changed and distinctly “modern” conceptualizations of political theory concepts such as freedom, responsibility, justice, rights and obligation, as central categories for organizing moral and political life. &#8232;&#8232;

Most students found the class interesting, engaging and informative. Many complained about the readings being too long, dense, and repetitive by the end of the semester. One student felt that lectures could have been more focused on what was important to take away from the philosophers. Another student was frustrated with the midterm paper topics, saying that they “were not presented in the best way possible. They were more conducive to lists than to a cohesive paper.”&#8232;&#8232;

Professor Hirschmann has been praised as a knowledgeable and engaging lecturer who commands the room with presence and is genuinely interested in the topic. She has been known to walk around the room during lecture and randomly call on students. While some felt that the assignments and lecture were stimulating, others felt Professor Hirschmann needed to work on organization. Some felt that their notes were sporadic and that they were lost during lecture. Students would have preferred that Professor Hirschmann outline where she was going with each lecture and the major points to take away from each author. One student commented that they only really had a grasp of the material after recitation.

This course is part of the core requirements for both the political science and PPE majors. It fulfills the History and Tradition sector requirement.

Students agreed that the course was \"challenging,\" but \"intellectually stimulating\" and \"satisfying\". A number of students stated that \"all texts required for the course [were] engaging\" and \"sometimes difficult to interpret,\" but with Professor Green\'s assistance each student was able to formulate a concrete and educated understanding and reaction to the readings. &#8232;

Students praised Professor Green for his hard work and dedication to his students. As one student said, \"He seems to love to teach and he CARES that we learn. That distinguishes him above most of my professors.\" All students said that Professor Green was characterized as \"knowledgeable, articulate, and engaging\" in addition to being accessible and willing to help with any confusion or question. Another student emphasized Professor Green\'s willingness to \"often ask the class for its opinion and treat the students as peers, which is extremely refreshing.\"

Some students complained about the difficulty and complexity of the paper topics as \"some of the concepts were so abstract,\" but concluded that Professor Green helped to make sense of them with excellent \"feedback.\" However, most students said that they would not recommend this course to a non-major or as a first for aspiring political scientists, stating \"this is the first political science course I have ever taken, and I feel that the level is more designed for an intermediate political science student than a beginner.\"

This course begins by exploring the causes and consequences of the rise of industrial Asia, paying particular attention to the role played by political institutions. It then examines the political economic challenges faced in recent years by many countries in this region. What explanations may be given for the rapid growth experienced in the region? And, how can we reconcile the success of the past with the difficulties experienced in more recent years? The role of national financial systems in supporting or undermining growth and the politics of financial crisis management and financial system reform will be explored in depth.

Students stated that the course was a “tough class to have in an hour” as there was a lot of material to cover in such a short period. Many students complained about the lack of variety as one student stated: “The class was too focused on Japan. Not enough about China” and one student went as far as to say, “if this is truly a course on ‘East Asia’, then it should address all of the countries in East Asia, including the smaller countries.” &#8232;&#8232;

Students stated that although Professor Amyx was an interesting teacher, she “often came to class with about 50 lecture slides she wanted to cover” and “in the. our of class we had, we usually only covered 10 slides”. However, Professor Amyx had to leave midway through the semester for a medical leave. The teaching assistants were “inexperienced” and unprepared, according to students. &#8232;
Although every review featured a negative aspect because the class was left to the T.A.s after Professor Amyx had to take a medical leave, students complained about the workload. One student stated that “most of the learning was pretty much done on our own, by having to catch up on slides and reading ahead for the next week.”

By examining Supreme Court decisions in light of works on American history, politics, and political theory, the class will explore legal, political, and philosophical debates on civil liberties today. Readings will consider litigation of the 1st, 2d, 4th, 5th, 8th, and 14th Amendments. Issues will include struggles over freedom of religion, speech, privacy, and property rights, analyzed in the context of American cultural traditions and hierarchies; and conflicts over the rights of suspects, criminals and citizens, analyzed in the context of racial and class tensions and criminal violence.

Students praised Professor Smith’s course calling it “my favorite course at Penn so far” and “simply fantastic.” Students also stated that the course was well-organized and structured. One student noted, “the course was well put together, the readings had a logical chronology and order”. One student said that the course structure and presentation really set it apart from similar classes, and commented, “I also got a good sense of the trends of the Court, which other constitutional law courses I have taken have failed to recognize.”&#8232;

Students raved about Professor Smith’s ability to teach and to liven the classroom setting. One student said, “Professor Smith is engaging and his subtle humor keeps class interesting. I especially appreciate the updates on current cases coming from the Supreme Court which highlight topics from class.” Students stated that Professor Smith’s incredible wealth of constitutional knowledge really set him apart from fellow professors as he did “a nice job of mixing the theoretical with the reality of the Court’s decisions over time.” &#8232;&#8232;

Students recommended this course to both majors and non-majors. Students emphasized their love for the Professor’s creativity and flexibility as one student said: “The midterm and final were both a strong assessment of what we had learned in the course and also extremely enjoyable. Pretending to be a justice handing down a decision is possibly the most exciting ‘test’ I could imagine. I would honestly not mind taking a test for this class everyday.”

The existence and endurance of war provides one of the most important puzzles of politics: why is it that people keep making use of such a destructive and painful way of resolving their disputes? This course addresses this question and related questions of what factors contribute to peace, focusing on both academic and popular explanations for conflict, including among others anarchy, over optimism, shifting power, diversionary war, the malevolent influence of war profiteers, and a variety of explanations grounded in culture, religion, and other ideational variables. The course discusses a wide range of historical and contemporary cases, including the World Wars, Vietnam, the Gulf War, the Iraq War, the various Arab-Israeli wars, the India-Pakistan rivalry, and a number of recent civil conflicts such as the wars in Yugoslavia, Congo, and Sudan. The course concludes with a discussion of strategies for managing ongoing conflicts and for securing peace in post-war settings.&#8232;&#8232;
Students taking this course found it to be interesting and challenging and most agreed that it was very informative. “I learned a lot about the nature of the international political realm,” said one student. Students also mentioned that the outline of the lectures was helpful and made it easier to review notes. Most of the students felt that the readings were relevant and interesting. &#8232;&#8232;
Overall students found Professor Weisiger to be very knowledgeable and a good instructor, although many felt that he rushed through the second half of the course and did not spend as much time as they felt was needed to explain some important concepts.&#8232;&#8232;
Most of the students who took this course said that there was a lot of reading. The midterm was in the form of a paper and a few students said they felt that they did not have enough time to review for it and the final exam. One student also mentioned that the format of the midterm was “unclear about how to properly answer the question.” Another student said the final exam was “quite daunting” because of the amount of material that had been covered. A few students mentioned that the grading was also tough. Overall most students were happy with the course, and one student recommended that it was “vital to anyone interested in international politics.”

This seminar offers an introduction to Muslim political thought from the medieval period to the present. Particular attention will be given in the later part of the course to the recent renaissance of Muslim political thought and to the development of political Islam, including the work of such thinkers as Said Qutb and Hasan Turabi. The class will also study the roots of this renaissance in classical philosophy of the medieval period (al Farabi, Al Ghazali, and Ibn Tufayl) and the liberal age. &#8232;&#8232;
Many students commented that the actual material and substance of the course was interesting, but that the course itself was “unorganized”, “ extremely scattered”, and “did not seem to be well planned”. One student also mentioned that “the issues discussed and the manner in which they were discussed was extremely philosophical.” Students also mentioned that the class discussion was often controlled by a “select group of students” who made “insensitive” and “empty” comments. One student said that if they “had known what they know now about the course, they would never have taken” while another student called the class “very interesting.” &#8232;&#8232;
The majority of students who took this course described Professor Norton as very knowledgeable and animated, but also criticized her as being unorganized and having a lack of focus and control over class discussions. One student said that the arguments that Professor Norton made were “not substantiated much of the time and quite often biased.”&#8232;
&#8232;Although no prerequisite is stated for this course, one student said that the “course should either require a prior history course to be taken on the ancient Middle East or should provide more background on the texts being read.” This person also said that “for people entirely unfamiliar with the region…, the course was very insignificant because [they] had no contextual framework to place the readings in.” One person also commented that Professor Norton would “assign whole books only to talk about a chapter; you really don\'t know at any time what you should read.” This person went on to say that the “assessments kept jumping about, as did instructions for the same.”

This class on American Constitutional politics examines constitutional controversies and the role that race and ethnicity play in them. It asks questions such as: What are “race” and “ethnicity”? How have American constitutional politics been shaped by issues of racial and ethnic statuses? How have American racial and ethnic identities and statuses been shaped by American constitutional politics? Has an “American Creed” of democratic liberalism dominated American culture, with racial hierarchies a frustrating exception? Or have ideologies of racial and ethnic identity and struggles over racial and ethnic statuses instead been central to American constitutional development? Secondary historical, legal, political and economic analyses will also be used to analyze these themes.&#8232;
&#8232;Students liked this interesting course that they said “challenged common notions of race in America.” They also liked that the format of the class involved class discussion about the reading assignments, which were “relevant” and “helpful.” One student also commented that the “subject matter… is presented in such a way that there\'s something for everyone.” Most students agreed that they learned a lot in this class, and a few students even described it as one of the best courses they had taken at Penn.
The majority of students commented that Professor Smith was an “excellent,” “amazing,” and “unbelievable” professor who was knowledgeable and “personable.” One student said that Professor Smith “did an admirable job of moderating the discussions so that everyone was able to contribute, and all of the material was covered in an interesting way.”&#8232;&#8232;
One student did mention that the class covered “an astonishing amount of material in a relatively short time” and another said that there was more reading in this course than they had ever had before. It was also suggested that “it would be convenient if footnotes were included with readings in the bulkpack.” The majority of students in this class were upperclassmen.

